This paper is about Dialogue State Tracking (DST) for task-oriented dialogues, which is a subfield of Natural Language Processing (NLP) and falls under the Computer Science category. The paper proposes a novel framework for Non-Autoregressive Dialog State Tracking (NADST), which optimizes the models towards better prediction of dialogue states as a complete set rather than separate slots. This work involves machine learning and deep learning techniques, which are commonly used in the sub-categories of Computational Linguistics (cs.CL), Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI), and Machine Learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper also discusses the latency reduction achieved by the proposed method, which is related to the sub-category of Systems and Control (cs.SD). Finally, the proposed method involves the detection of dependencies among slots, which is a problem of Neural Networks (cs.NE). Therefore, the most likely arXiv CS sub-categories for this paper are cs.CL, cs.AI, cs.LG, cs.SD, and cs.NE, in that order.
